  <h2>Common Vulnerabilities Discovered</h2>

  <p>
    Based on real-world MobSF scans, here are the most common Android security issues:
  </p>

  <h3>1. Insecure Data Storage</h3>
  <pre><code>{`// Vulnerable code found in SharedPreferences
SharedPreferences prefs = getSharedPreferences("user_data", MODE_WORLD_READABLE);
prefs.edit().putString("password", userPassword).apply();

// Issue: Password stored in plaintext, accessible by other apps`}</code></pre>

  <h3>2. Insufficient Transport Security</h3>
  <pre><code>{`// No certificate pinning or SSL validation
TrustManager[] trustAllCerts = new TrustManager[]{
    new X509TrustManager() {
        public void checkClientTrusted(X509Certificate[] chain, String authType) {}
        public void checkServerTrusted(X509Certificate[] chain, String authType) {}
        public X509Certificate[] getAcceptedIssuers() { return new X509Certificate[0]; }
    }
};`}</code></pre>

  <h3>3. Exported Components</h3>
  <pre><code>{`<!-- Vulnerable manifest entry -->
<activity android:name=".SecretActivity"
          android:exported="true">
    <intent-filter>
        <action android:name="com.example.SECRET_ACTION"/>
    </intent-filter>
</activity>

<!-- Can be exploited by any app to access SecretActivity -->`}</code></pre>

